s not a big deal,<br />and it seems to perform very much as advertized. The difference with<br />autogroup scheduling is very noticeable with a simple "make -j64"<br />kernel compile.<br /><br />So I really don't think it's a big deal. The sysctl handler isn't even<br />complicated. But boy does it hurt my eyes to see a spinlock held<br />around a "do_each_thread()". And I do get the feeling that the<br />simplest way to fix it would be to just remove the code entirely, and<br />just say that "enabling/disabling may be delayed for old processes<br />with existing autogroups".<br /><br />                    Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
